    {
      "type": "mathjax",
      "id": "9938686177852707",
      "text": "The juridification of the world - this denotes the dark side of the value-added compulsion in law. Its irrepressible drive for universalization is driven by the temptation that law seeks to subject the whole of society to the logic of the juridical pursuit of justice. Instead of respecting the quite different requirements of political distributive justice or moral respect justice and limiting itself to conflict resolution, the legal system, in \"acute justice fever,\" seeks to realize a just society by the means of juridical justice. It is just to decide the problems of the world according to the binary code right/wrong - this is the summum ius, summa iniuria in the functionally differentiated society. It shares this urge with other [[Contingency Formulas]], with that of economics, which tries to describe the whole world as a problem of scarcity to be solved by economic means, with that of the legitimacy formula of politics, and with that of the limitationality of science. They all try to increase their surplus-value production by society-wide expansion, promising to be able to produce a good society with their means, although they can only give extremely limited partial answers for their domain. \"Justification\" of society is one of the baleful surplus-value imperialisms of modernity, along with economization, politicization, scientization, moralization, medicalization of society – an unidirectional process of increase against which political vigilance is needed. The imperialism of a merely partial orientation to surplus value is so dangerous because it accommodates people's desire for an indivisible justice even in today's society, although it knows that this desire cannot be satisfied in principle in modernity, and yet it makes a false promise of salvation with juridical justice, which arrogates itself to justice for the whole of society. Both produce a dangerous brew of unanswerable questions and mendacious answers. "
